docs.lead_paragraph: The Affordable Care Act provided a big increase in Medicaid payments for primary care the past two years, but the higher fees expire Thursday, raising questions of whether there will be enough doctors to provide services.

headline.main: As Medicaid Rolls Swell, Cuts in Payments to Doctors Threaten Access to Care
headline.print_headline: As Medicaid Rolls Swell, Cuts in Payments to Doctors Threaten Access to Care

docs.abstract: Medicaid is prepared to make deep cuts in doctors' payments as increases from Affordable Care Act are about to expire; in many states primary care services rates are likely to fall to 2012 levels, which are not seen as adequate enough; cuts raise concerns that less patients will have access to care.
docs.snippet: The Affordable Care Act provided a big increase in Medicaid payments for primary care the past two years, but the higher fees expire Thursday, raising questions of whether there will be enough doctors to provide services.
